[[Category:Mountains of Togo|Agou]] [[Category:Highest points of countries]]
{{Togo-geo-stub}}

[[File:Multimap fromlivesearch.png|right|thumb|Multimap.com]] '''Multimap.com''' was a [[United Kingdom]] based provider of mapping and [[location-based service]]s. It was acquired by Microsoft in 2007 and merged into [[Bing Maps]] in 2010.<ref>[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/media/article3040853.ece Microsoft swoop hands Multimap founder $25m]{{dead link|date=November 2018}}</ref>
==History== Multimap.com was founded circa 1997.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010603190148/http://www.multimap.com/indexes/aboutindex.htm Multimap.com about page], Internet Archive Wayback Machine, June 20, 2001</ref> It offered street maps and door-to-door travel directions on a public web site. Other offerings included [[aerial photography|aerial photographs]], local information, and business services. Services were also offered through its partners, including accommodation, restaurant and train-ticket booking. It also sold historic and aerial photograph prints. In 2004 the public web site regularly delivered more than 160 million page views per month and received more than 7.3 million unique users per quarter.
Unlike later online maps such as [[Google Maps]], Multimap offered discrete panning by clicking links, a form of user interaction later displaced by continuous panning [[Tiled web map|'slippy' maps]].
The [[Geo (microformat)|Geo microformat]] is used to provide a Wikipedia map overlay generated from the official [[Wikipedia:Database download|database download]]. This is used to browse [[Geotagging|geotagged]] articles.
In December 2007, the company was bought by [[Microsoft]].<ref>[http://news.microsoft.com/2007/12/12/microsoft-acquires-one-of-europes-top-online-map-services/ Microsoft Acquires One of Europe's Top Online Map Services], Press Release, December 12, 2007</ref> In 2010{{fact|date=November 2018}} it was merged into Microsoft's Bing Maps service.
==See also== * [[OpenStreetMap]]
